{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654299"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18614"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18614"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76435"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11346"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61932"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10277"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26340"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76435"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESkeletal muscle contains different fibre types that are specialised for specific functional roles. Fast oxidative glycolytic (FOG) fibres represent an intermediate fibre type with distinct metabolic and contractile properties.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the characteristics of fast oxidative glycolytic muscle fibres?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Low glycolytic capacity with many mitochondria","Slow contraction speed with high fatigue resistance","High oxidative and glycolytic capacity with rapid contraction speed","High glycolytic capacity with few mitochondria","Low oxidative capacity with slow contraction speed"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFast oxidative glycolytic (FOG) fibres are characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh oxidative and glycolytic capacity with rapid contraction speed\u003C/strong\u003E. These fibres contain numerous mitochondria for oxidative metabolism while also maintaining substantial glycolytic enzymes. Their high myosin ATPase activity enables rapid cross-bridge cycling and fast contractions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow oxidative capacity with slow contraction speed\u003C/strong\u003E - FOG fibres have high oxidative capacity and contract rapidly\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh glycolytic capacity with few mitochondria\u003C/strong\u003E - While FOG fibres have high glycolytic capacity, they also possess abundant mitochondria\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow glycolytic capacity with many mitochondria\u003C/strong\u003E - FOG fibres maintain high glycolytic capacity alongside their oxidative capabilities\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESlow contraction speed with high fatigue resistance\u003C/strong\u003E - FOG fibres contract rapidly, though they do have moderate fatigue resistance\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese properties make FOG fibres well-suited for sustained activities requiring moderate force output, such as maintaining posture or repetitive movements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fast oxidative glycolytic (FOG) muscle fibres combine characteristics of both aerobic and anaerobic metabolism.","FOG fibres have numerous mitochondria and myoglobin, allowing sustained activity at moderate intensities.","FOG fibres contract rapidly and generate significant force due to their high myosin ATPase activity."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61932"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18614"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61932"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T14:07:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T14:07:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11346"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76435"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musc